Stay till the end and I'll show you  

5
00:00:11,560 --> 00:00:14,920
what you've been missing!
 
When you place a trade,  

6
00:00:14,920 --> 00:00:19,800
you're full of hope and expectations.
Every time you enter, you're very  

7
00:00:19,800 --> 00:00:26,440
confident the market will move in your favor. 
 
But often, almost as soon as you enter a trade,  

8
00:00:26,440 --> 00:00:32,520
the price starts moving in the opposite direction.
And in most cases, it all starts with  

9
00:00:32,520 --> 00:00:36,280
a manipulation candle.
A manipulation candle is  

10
00:00:36,280 --> 00:00:43,720
a price action pattern used by market makers, to 
trick novice traders into taking losing positions. 

11
00:00:43,720 --> 00:00:47,240
These candles are designed 
to create false signals,  

12
00:00:47,240 --> 00:00:53,440
that often lead to poor trading decisions.
 
Market makers, who have significant capital,  

13
00:00:53,440 --> 00:00:59,600
can move prices in ways that trigger 
stop losses and create false breakouts. 

14
00:00:59,600 --> 00:01:05,000
They do this to collect liquidity from 
other traders who often enter and place  

15
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:11,400
their stop losses in predictable locations.
 
And it's not just a single candle, but a whole  

16
00:01:11,400 --> 00:01:18,240
sequence of price moves designed to trick traders.
So let’s talk about it, these are the most common  

17
00:01:18,240 --> 00:01:22,257
manipulation candles.
 
Candles with Big Wicks

18
00:01:22,257 --> 00:01:24,640
Candles with big wicks are 
some of the most deceptive and  

19
00:01:24,640 --> 00:01:31,040
manipulative tools used in the market.
At the core, big wicks represent areas  

20
00:01:31,040 --> 00:01:36,520
where the price moved significantly 
in one direction, but failed to hold. 

21
00:01:36,520 --> 00:01:41,240
The long wick shows price rejection, 
meaning it reached a point where the  

22
00:01:41,240 --> 00:01:47,240
market didn’t want to stay. This happens 
because large players are moving the price,  

23
00:01:47,240 --> 00:01:53,880
to trigger certain actions from retail traders.
 
Big players know where most retail traders  

24
00:01:53,880 --> 00:01:59,040
place their stop-losses, or where 
breakout traders are waiting to enter. 

25
00:01:59,040 --> 00:02:04,080
And by pushing the price to these 
levels, they can activate these orders,  

26
00:02:04,080 --> 00:02:11,760
only to reverse the price and trap those traders.
The wick is the aftermath of this manipulation.
  

27
00:02:11,760 --> 00:02:17,440
The manipulation works because most 
novice traders react to price movements,  

28
00:02:17,440 --> 00:02:23,480
without considering the intention behind them.
The big players push the price up or down  

29
00:02:23,480 --> 00:02:30,000
aggressively, creating a sense of urgency.
Traders see this sudden move and think they’re  

30
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:34,600
missing out on a potential 
breakout or trend continuation. 

31
00:02:34,600 --> 00:02:40,360
The wick itself is the result of this push.
 
Breakout traders also enter the market,  

32
00:02:40,360 --> 00:02:44,680
thinking the move is real.
At the same time, traders who  

33
00:02:44,680 --> 00:02:50,880
had their stop losses set just beyond key 
levels, get forced out of their trades. 

34
00:02:50,880 --> 00:02:57,520
These traders think the market is breaking out 
of a range, or continuing in a strong direction.
  

35
00:02:57,520 --> 00:03:02,960
And once the big players have triggered 
enough orders and collected liquidity,  

36
00:03:02,960 --> 00:03:07,080
they reverse the price.
The candle closes far from  

37
00:03:07,080 --> 00:03:14,520
the extreme point of the wick, showing a large 
rejection of that price level. Retail traders  

38
00:03:14,520 --> 00:03:20,200
who entered the market on the breakout are 
now trapped in losing positions, while those  

39
00:03:20,200 --> 00:03:26,480
who got stopped out are left frustrated.
This manipulation relies on the fact that  

40
00:03:26,480 --> 00:03:31,240
traders tend to follow price blindly, 
without understanding that the price  

41
00:03:31,240 --> 00:03:38,400
move was intentionally created to trap them.
 
Once you understand how this manipulation works,  

42
00:03:38,400 --> 00:03:43,840
you can use it to your advantage.
First, don’t jump into trades just  

43
00:03:43,840 --> 00:03:50,640
because the price moves past a key level.
Instead, wait to see how the candle closes. 
  

44
00:03:50,640 --> 00:03:57,720
If the candle has a big wick and closes near its 
opening price (indicating rejection), this is a  

45
00:03:57,720 --> 00:04:03,760
sign that the previous breakout might be false.
You can then consider entering a trade in  

46
00:04:03,760 --> 00:04:08,160
the opposite direction.
 
Second, big wicks often  

47
00:04:08,160 --> 00:04:14,640
occur around major levels. These are areas 
where big players know that traders have  

48
00:04:14,640 --> 00:04:21,680
placed their stop losses or breakout orders.
If you see a long wick forming at a key level,  

49
00:04:21,680 --> 00:04:25,920
it’s a sign that the big players 
are hunting for liquidity. 

50
00:04:25,920 --> 00:04:31,840
You can use this as a signal to enter a 
trade in the opposite direction of the wick.
  

51
00:04:31,840 --> 00:04:36,640
Also, wicks are more common during 
certain phases of the market. 

52
00:04:36,640 --> 00:04:41,920
In consolidation phases, big 
players are accumulating positions,  

53
00:04:41,920 --> 00:04:47,680
and they use wicks to mislead traders 
into thinking the market is breaking out. 

54
00:04:47,680 --> 00:04:53,280
Once they’ve accumulated enough positions, 
they’ll move the market in the real direction,  

55
00:04:53,280 --> 00:04:58,840
often leaving a series of wicks 
behind as a trail of manipulation.
  

56
00:04:58,840 --> 00:05:04,320
The longer the wick, the stronger the 
manipulation. A very long wick shows  

57
00:05:04,320 --> 00:05:10,800
that big players pushed the price far in 
one direction, only to reverse it quickly. 

58
00:05:10,800 --> 00:05:14,920
This is a sign that they’re 
actively trying to trap traders. 

59
00:05:14,920 --> 00:05:21,960
Shorter wicks, on the other hand, might just 
be a sign of indecision or weak momentum. 
  

60
00:05:21,960 --> 00:05:27,400
If you see multiple long wicks forming 
at the same level, it’s a strong sign. 

61
00:05:27,400 --> 00:05:33,040
The big players are repeatedly pushing 
the price to that level to trigger orders,  

62
00:05:33,040 --> 00:05:37,680
but the price keeps getting rejected.
This is a sign that the market is about  

63
00:05:37,680 --> 00:05:42,000
to move in the opposite direction.
If you see this setup,  

64
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:48,040
it’s a good opportunity to enter a trade 
against the direction of the wicks.
 
  

65
00:05:48,040 --> 00:05:50,640
Large Candles in Sideways Markets
Large candles in sideways markets are  

66
00:05:50,640 --> 00:05:56,480
another classic manipulation tactic.
These candles may even break out of a range,  

67
00:05:56,480 --> 00:05:59,640
causing traders to believe 
a strong movement has begun,  

68
00:06:00,320 --> 00:06:06,800
only for the price to reverse shortly afterward. 
 
When the market is moving sideways, it means  

69
00:06:06,800 --> 00:06:12,600
there’s a period of accumulation or indecision.
Prices are stuck within a range, bouncing between  

70
00:06:12,600 --> 00:06:17,040
support and resistance levels.
And big players use these  

71
00:06:17,040 --> 00:06:22,480
periods to build their positions.
But they also need liquidity to execute large  

72
00:06:22,480 --> 00:06:29,160
trades, without moving the market too much. 
 
This is where large candles come into play. 

73
00:06:29,160 --> 00:06:36,240
What happens is that these big players push the 
price suddenly in one direction, to create FOMO. 

74
00:06:36,240 --> 00:06:42,080
Reactive traders see the large candle and 
enter the market, expecting the price to  

75
00:06:42,080 --> 00:06:47,880
continue in the direction of the candle. 
 
This adds more liquidity for the big players,  

76
00:06:47,880 --> 00:06:53,760
to take the opposite side of the trade.
The large candle is essentially a trap. It  

77
00:06:53,760 --> 00:06:59,640
gives the illusion of a strong directional 
move, but in reality, it’s a manipulation  

78
00:06:59,640 --> 00:07:03,600
tactic to create liquidity.
 
The candle may even break  

79
00:07:03,600 --> 00:07:07,840
outside the previous range.
This is a classic liquidity grab,  

80
00:07:07,840 --> 00:07:13,240
where big players need stop-loss 
orders to fill their own positions. 

81
00:07:13,240 --> 00:07:19,720
These candles create emotional reactions in 
traders. A sudden big move can make traders think  

82
00:07:19,720 --> 00:07:26,480
they’re missing out on an opportunity, causing 
them to enter trades without proper confirmation.  

83
00:07:26,480 --> 00:07:32,840
This is a classic case of “Fear of Missing Out”. 
 
I’ve personally done it dozens of times,  

84
00:07:32,840 --> 00:07:38,800
rushing into the market, thinking a large 
candle signals the start of a new trend. 

85
00:07:38,800 --> 00:07:45,320
To avoid getting trapped, volume is my go-to 
indicator when I’m facing a large candle. 

86
00:07:45,320 --> 00:07:50,800
If the candle forms on high volume but 
the price quickly reverses, it’s a strong  

87
00:07:50,800 --> 00:07:56,240
sign that the move was actually a trap.
Big players were likely using the volume  

88
00:07:56,240 --> 00:08:03,400
spike to create liquidity for their own trades.
On the other hand, if a large candle forms on low  

89
00:08:03,400 --> 00:08:10,960
volume, it might be a sign of weak conviction, 
and the breakout might not be sustainable.
  

90
00:08:10,960 --> 00:08:16,520
Sometimes, you’ll see multiple large 
candles forming in quick succession. 

91
00:08:16,520 --> 00:08:22,320
This is another manipulation tactic. Big 
players will push the price in one direction,  

92
00:08:22,320 --> 00:08:28,200
then reverse it, then push it again, 
creating a series of large candles. 

93
00:08:28,200 --> 00:08:34,560
This confuses traders, making them unsure 
of whether the move is real or false. 

94
00:08:34,560 --> 00:08:38,560
If you see multiple large candles 
forming in a sideways market,  

95
00:08:38,560 --> 00:08:45,200
it’s a sign that manipulation is at play, and 
you should be cautious about entering a trade.
 
  

96
00:08:45,200 --> 00:08:48,720
Inside Bars Followed by Weak Breakouts
Inside bars followed by weak breakouts are  

97
00:08:48,720 --> 00:08:52,840
one of the classic setups that 
can often lead to losing trades. 

98
00:08:52,840 --> 00:08:59,080
An inside bar is a candle that forms completely 
within the range of the previous candle. 

99
00:08:59,080 --> 00:09:04,320
Think of it as a sign of indecision 
or consolidation in the market. 

100
00:09:04,320 --> 00:09:09,720
The price isn’t moving much, and traders 
are waiting for something to happen. 
  

101
00:09:09,720 --> 00:09:13,880
Because the price is “stuck” within 
the range of the previous candle,  

102
00:09:13,880 --> 00:09:19,520
traders know a breakout could be coming, 
and they start preparing to enter trades,  

103
00:09:19,520 --> 00:09:23,760
based on whether the breakout 
is bullish or bearish. 

104
00:09:23,760 --> 00:09:29,360
And when a series of inside bars form, 
it amplifies the anticipation even more. 

105
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:33,960
Traders are waiting for the 
market to break out of this chop. 

106
00:09:33,960 --> 00:09:39,600
They know that once the price breaks out of 
the range, it could lead to a strong move. 
  

107
00:09:39,600 --> 00:09:43,040
This is where the manipulation 
starts to take root. 

108
00:09:43,040 --> 00:09:47,600
Well, during this time, big players 
are building their positions. 

109
00:09:47,600 --> 00:09:52,720
They don’t want to reveal their hand, so 
they keep the market within a tight range. 

110
00:09:52,720 --> 00:09:57,360
Novice traders, on the other hand, 
are getting ready for a breakout. 

111
00:09:57,360 --> 00:10:03,920
A lot of retail traders start placing orders 
just outside the range of the inside bars. 

112
00:10:03,920 --> 00:10:10,040
Buyers will place buy orders just above 
the high of the inside bar, while sellers  

113
00:10:10,040 --> 00:10:16,840
will place sell orders just below the low.
This is exactly what big players want. They  

114
00:10:16,840 --> 00:10:23,400
are setting a trap by making the market look 
like it’s ready to explode in one direction.
  

115
00:10:23,400 --> 00:10:29,640
Then, the breakout happens. A candle breaks 
out of the range of the inside bars. This  

116
00:10:29,640 --> 00:10:37,800
breakout candle may look extremely convincing.
It’s big, fast, and it creates a sense of urgency. 

117
00:10:37,800 --> 00:10:44,000
Many traders enter the market at this point. They 
believe the breakout is real, and they don’t want  

118
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:49,000
to miss out on the potential profits. 
 
And this is exactly what the big players  

119
00:10:49,000 --> 00:10:54,720
want. They’ve lured the traders into 
the market at the worst possible moment. 

120
00:10:54,720 --> 00:11:00,840
Then the price reverses sharply. The breakout 
candle that looked so convincing is suddenly  

121
00:11:00,840 --> 00:11:06,320
followed by a reversal candle, and the 
price moves in the other direction. 

122
00:11:06,320 --> 00:11:12,120
Traders who entered on the breakout 
are now trapped in losing positions. 
  

123
00:11:12,120 --> 00:11:17,520
This manipulation works because it preys 
on the natural instincts of traders. 

124
00:11:17,520 --> 00:11:25,320
Inside bars create a sense of anticipation, 
and breakout candles create a sense of urgency. 

125
00:11:25,320 --> 00:11:29,560
When we see a large candle breaking 
out of a consolidation zone,  

126
00:11:29,560 --> 00:11:35,000
we assume it’s the start of a new trend.
We don’t want to miss out on the move, so we  

127
00:11:35,000 --> 00:11:41,480
enter the market without waiting for confirmation.
This is exactly the reaction that big players  

128
00:11:41,480 --> 00:11:44,200
are counting on.
 
The key to avoiding  

129
00:11:44,200 --> 00:11:50,200
this type of setup is confirmation.
After the breakout candle forms, wait to see the  

130
00:11:50,200 --> 00:11:56,680
price reaction when it retests the breakout level.
If the breakout is real, the price will often  

131
00:11:56,680 --> 00:12:02,400
pull back to the breakout level, and then 
continue in the direction of the breakout. 

132
00:12:02,400 --> 00:12:09,120
If the price breaks out and then quickly reverses, 
it’s a sign that the breakout was false.
  

133
00:12:09,120 --> 00:12:15,200
And second, a real breakout is often 
accompanied by a significant increase in volume. 

134
00:12:15,200 --> 00:12:20,400
If the breakout candle forms but there’s no 
increase in volume, it could be a sign that the  

135
00:12:20,400 --> 00:12:24,440
breakout is weak and likely to reverse. 
 
 
Bullish/Bearish Kicker 

136
00:12:24,440 --> 00:12:30,240
Bullish and Bearish Kicker patterns 
are also common manipulate on patterns. 

137
00:12:30,240 --> 00:12:35,720
These often involve a gap, followed by a strong 
move in the opposite direction of the previous  

138
00:12:35,720 --> 00:12:42,720
trend, catching many traders by surprise. 
 
A Bullish Kicker happens after a downtrend, right  

139
00:12:42,720 --> 00:12:48,600
at the New York open. The market gaps down at the 
open, but instead of continuing in the direction  

140
00:12:48,600 --> 00:12:55,880
of the downtrend, it reverses sharply and moves 
upward, forming a strong bullish candle.  
  

141
00:12:55,880 --> 00:13:01,920
A Bearish Kicker happens after an uptrend. 
The market gaps up at the open, but instead  

142
00:13:01,920 --> 00:13:09,560
of continuing higher, it reverses sharply and 
moves downward, forming a strong bearish candle. 
  

143
00:13:09,560 --> 00:13:15,280
Kicker patterns primarily occur because of 
a sudden shift in sentiment in the market. 

144
00:13:15,280 --> 00:13:21,760
But this shift isn’t always organic. 
Often, it’s manufactured by bigger players. 

145
00:13:21,760 --> 00:13:25,440
Just like with many other 
manipulative tactics, the main goal  

146
00:13:25,440 --> 00:13:32,240
of a Kicker pattern is to create liquidity. 
 
For instance, in a Bearish Kicker, traders who  

147
00:13:32,240 --> 00:13:39,280
are long will typically have their stop-loss 
orders placed just below key support levels. 

148
00:13:39,280 --> 00:13:44,560
By pushing the price up and then sharply 
reversing, big players can trigger those  

149
00:13:44,560 --> 00:13:50,760
stop-losses, creating the liquidity they 
need to enter their own short positions.
  

150
00:13:50,760 --> 00:13:57,720
Kicker patterns prey on traders’ emotions.
In a Bullish Kicker, the market may gap down,  

151
00:13:57,720 --> 00:14:03,400
and traders will assume that the downtrend 
will continue. But when the price suddenly  

152
00:14:03,400 --> 00:14:09,720
reverses and moves upward, traders 
get confused and start to panic. 

153
00:14:09,720 --> 00:14:16,480
This panic leads many traders to exit their 
positions at a loss or reverse their trades,  

154
00:14:16,480 --> 00:14:22,400
which plays into the hands of big players.
 
The manipulation process in Kicker patterns  

155
00:14:22,400 --> 00:14:27,480
works because of a combination of 
psychological and technical traps. 

156
00:14:27,480 --> 00:14:31,160
The first part of the 
manipulation involves the gap. 

157
00:14:31,160 --> 00:14:36,040
This gap is designed to make traders 
think the trend is going to continue. 
  

158
00:14:36,040 --> 00:14:40,040
For example, when the market 
gaps down in a Bullish Kicker,  

159
00:14:40,040 --> 00:14:46,360
traders believe that the downtrend is still 
intact and that the price will continue to fall. 

160
00:14:46,360 --> 00:14:51,320
So, at the market open, many 
traders enter short positions. 

161
00:14:51,320 --> 00:14:58,160
But after the gap, the price suddenly reverses 
and moves strongly in the opposite direction. 

162
00:14:58,160 --> 00:15:02,600
This is where the manipulation 
becomes obvious. Traders who  

163
00:15:02,600 --> 00:15:09,400
entered short positions after the gap are now 
trapped. as the price moves against them. 
  

164
00:15:09,400 --> 00:15:12,160
As the price moves in the opposite direction,  

165
00:15:12,160 --> 00:15:18,520
it triggers stop-losses that were placed 
by sellers on the wrong side of the market. 

166
00:15:18,520 --> 00:15:23,320
This creates liquidity for big 
players to enter their positions. 

167
00:15:23,320 --> 00:15:29,320
This allows them to buy at lower prices 
before the price continues higher.
  

168
00:15:29,320 --> 00:15:34,760
Big players create the Kicker pattern 
to induce fear and confusion, causing  

169
00:15:34,760 --> 00:15:41,040
reactive traders to make emotional decisions.
Many of them will exit their positions in a  

170
00:15:41,040 --> 00:15:47,120
panic, while others will reverse their 
trades, trying to catch the new move. 
 

171
00:15:47,120 --> 00:15:53,160
Volume can provide clues about whether 
the Kicker pattern is real or manipulated. 

172
00:15:53,160 --> 00:15:59,120
If the gap and the strong move in the opposite 
direction are accompanied by high volume,  

173
00:15:59,120 --> 00:16:05,120
it’s more likely that the move is legitimate. 
 
One of the best ways to capitalize on Kicker  

174
00:16:05,120 --> 00:16:09,920
patterns is to trade the reversal.
Once you see that the initial breakout  

175
00:16:09,920 --> 00:16:16,480
was false and the price is reversing, you 
can enter a trade in the opposite direction. 

176
00:16:16,480 --> 00:16:23,080
For example, if you see a Bullish Kicker and 
the price quickly reverses after the gap,  

177
00:16:23,080 --> 00:16:29,080
you can enter a short position, expecting 
the price to continue downwards 
 
  

178
00:16:29,080 --> 00:16:29,827
Spinning Top

179
00:16:29,827 --> 00:16:35,120
Spinning top candles are fascinating because 
they represent indecision in the market. 

180
00:16:35,120 --> 00:16:39,240
These candles have small real 
bodies, regardless of whether  

181
00:16:39,240 --> 00:16:45,080
they are bullish or bearish, and they 
come with long wicks on both sides. 

182
00:16:45,080 --> 00:16:51,120
The small body shows that there wasn’t much 
movement between the opening and closing prices. 

183
00:16:51,120 --> 00:16:55,440
The long wicks indicate that 
both buyers and sellers had their  

184
00:16:55,440 --> 00:17:00,800
moments of control during the period. 
 
The result is a candle that tells us the  

185
00:17:00,800 --> 00:17:07,600
market isn’t sure where it wants to go next.
This candle traps both buyers and sellers,  

186
00:17:07,600 --> 00:17:10,628
having large wicks on both sides.
But spinning tops aren’t just about  

187
00:17:10,628 --> 00:17:15,040
indecision. They also present opportunities 
for manipulation, especially when they  

188
00:17:15,040 --> 00:17:20,280
appear at key levels in the market. 
 
So here, the market is in an uptrend,  

189
00:17:20,280 --> 00:17:25,040
and then a spinning top appears.
It implies that neither the buyers nor  

190
00:17:25,040 --> 00:17:30,440
the sellers had enough momentum to push 
the price decisively in one direction. 

191
00:17:30,440 --> 00:17:35,800
The market is essentially “taking a 
break,” reassessing its next move.
  

192
00:17:35,800 --> 00:17:39,560
These candles often appear 
at the end of a big move,  

193
00:17:39,560 --> 00:17:46,000
signaling that the trend might be losing steam.
This spinning top might indicate that the buyers  

194
00:17:46,000 --> 00:17:53,320
are getting tired, and the sellers might soon 
take control, potentially leading to a reversal. 
 

195
00:17:53,320 --> 00:17:59,000
However, spinning tops are often used 
as tools for market manipulation because  

196
00:17:59,000 --> 00:18:03,840
they play on traders’ emotions.
When traders see a spinning top,  

197
00:18:03,840 --> 00:18:09,280
they know it represents indecision in the market.
Many traders interpret this as a sign that  

198
00:18:09,280 --> 00:18:15,120
a big move is coming, especially if the 
spinning top forms at the end of a trend. 

199
00:18:15,120 --> 00:18:20,680
They believe that the market is “pausing” 
before making its next big move, and they  

200
00:18:20,680 --> 00:18:27,080
start positioning themselves for that move.
Beginners are taught to place buy orders above  

201
00:18:27,080 --> 00:18:32,080
the high of the spinning top, 
or sell orders below the low.
  

202
00:18:32,080 --> 00:18:37,200
This is where the manipulation comes 
in. Big players know that novice traders  

203
00:18:37,200 --> 00:18:42,480
are waiting for a breakout. They use 
this anticipation to their advantage. 

204
00:18:42,480 --> 00:18:49,040
They’ll push the price just high enough to 
trigger the buy orders placed by bullish traders,  

205
00:18:49,040 --> 00:18:54,200
or just low enough to trigger the 
sell orders placed by bearish traders. 

206
00:18:54,200 --> 00:18:58,720
And once the big players have triggered 
these orders, they reverse the price. 
  

207
00:18:59,680 --> 00:19:04,760
For example, let’s say a spinning 
top forms after a momentum up move. 

208
00:19:04,760 --> 00:19:10,680
Traders place buy orders above the high of the 
spinning top, thinking the market will continue  

209
00:19:10,680 --> 00:19:18,280
higher. The big players push the price just above 
the high to trigger those buy orders, then quickly  

210
00:19:18,280 --> 00:19:24,400
reverse the price, causing the market to drop.
The traders who entered long positions  

211
00:19:24,400 --> 00:19:29,400
are now trapped in losing trades.
 
And they rush to close their positions,  

212
00:19:29,400 --> 00:19:36,000
adding even more momentum to the reversal.
This is exactly what the big players want. 

213
00:19:36,000 --> 00:19:41,680
They’ve engineered the move to create panic 
and force traders to exit their positions at  

214
00:19:41,680 --> 00:19:48,120
a loss, all while profiting from the 
liquidity created by those exits.
 
  

215
00:19:48,120 --> 00:19:51,600
Volume can confirm whether a 
spinning top is likely to lead  

216
00:19:51,600 --> 00:19:57,760
to a real move or if it’s just a trap.
If the spinning top forms on low volume,  

217
00:19:57,760 --> 00:20:03,240
it could be a sign that the market is 
indecisive and that the breakout will be weak. 

218
00:20:03,240 --> 00:20:09,160
On the other hand, if the spinning top forms on 
high volume, it could indicate that there’s real  

219
00:20:09,160 --> 00:20:16,120
buying or selling pressure behind the move. 
 
One of the best ways to avoid getting trapped  

220
00:20:16,120 --> 00:20:22,720
is to wait for a retest of the breakout level.
For instance, if a spinning top forms at the end  

221
00:20:22,720 --> 00:20:28,000
of an uptrend and the price breaks 
below the low of the spinning top,  

222
00:20:28,000 --> 00:20:33,480
wait to see if the price retests that 
level before entering a short position. 

223
00:20:33,480 --> 00:20:40,480
If the price bounces off the retest and continues 
lower, it’s a sign that the breakdown is real. 

224
00:20:40,480 --> 00:20:45,920
If the price moves back above the level, 
it’s a sign that the breakdown was false,  

225
00:20:45,920 --> 00:20:52,880
and you should avoid entering a short position.
 
And be aware of key levels. Spinning tops are  

226
00:20:52,880 --> 00:20:58,120
most effective when they form at 
key support or resistance levels. 

227
00:20:58,120 --> 00:21:03,400
Sometimes, you’ll see multiple spinning tops 
forming in a row. This is a sign that the  

228
00:21:03,400 --> 00:21:09,760
market is in a prolonged state of indecision. 
 
While this might seem like a strong signal that  

229
00:21:09,760 --> 00:21:15,080
a big move is coming, be careful.
Big players know that traders are  

230
00:21:15,080 --> 00:21:22,040
watching these patterns, and they’ll often use the 
series of spinning tops to set up a bigger trap. 

231
00:21:22,040 --> 00:21:27,800
If you see multiple spinning tops forming, 
it’s a sign that you should be extra cautious  

232
00:21:27,800 --> 00:21:30,360
about entering a trade.
 
Weekly Candle Manipulation

233
00:21:30,360 --> 00:21:36,400
On higher timeframes like the weekly chart, 
manipulation tends to follow a pattern. 
  

234
00:21:36,400 --> 00:21:40,560
For example, the price opens at 
the start of the week and trades  

235
00:21:40,560 --> 00:21:45,800
near the opening level for a few days.
Then, the price moves sharply in one  

236
00:21:45,800 --> 00:21:51,600
direction. Traders think this is a 
real move and enter their trades. 

237
00:21:51,600 --> 00:21:58,920
Finally, the price reverses, trapping those 
traders and completing the manipulation phase. 

238
00:21:58,920 --> 00:22:04,400
This type of manipulation is powerful 
because it plays out over several days,  

239
00:22:04,400 --> 00:22:10,480
making it harder for traders to spot.
Big players use this strategy to build their  

240
00:22:10,480 --> 00:22:17,720
positions slowly before making the real move.
 
So on higher timeframes like the weekly chart,  

241
00:22:17,720 --> 00:22:22,560
manipulation plays out in a more 
deliberate and extended manner,  

242
00:22:22,560 --> 00:22:29,200
making it harder for retail traders to detect.
This manipulation process occurs in distinct  

243
00:22:29,200 --> 00:22:34,600
phases, allowing big players to 
build and distribute their positions,  

244
00:22:34,600 --> 00:22:41,480
while misleading retail traders along the way. 
 
The weekly chart, in particular, is an ideal  

245
00:22:41,480 --> 00:22:47,680
playground for large institutions, because the 
moves are more spread out, giving the illusion  

246
00:22:47,680 --> 00:22:55,000
of a natural price progression over several days.
At the start of the week, the price often opens  

247
00:22:55,000 --> 00:23:02,120
and trades near the opening level for a few days.
This is the accumulation phase. During this time,  

248
00:23:02,120 --> 00:23:06,160
the big players are quietly 
building their positions. 

249
00:23:06,160 --> 00:23:11,720
The price moves within a narrow range, 
often showing little volatility. 

250
00:23:11,720 --> 00:23:18,080
To the untrained eye, this sideways movement 
may seem uneventful, but this is where the  

251
00:23:18,080 --> 00:23:25,240
groundwork for the upcoming manipulation is laid.
 
Accumulation can be deceptive because it often  

252
00:23:25,240 --> 00:23:32,800
looks like a period of indecision in the market.
Retail traders might interpret this as a lack  

253
00:23:32,800 --> 00:23:38,080
of opportunity, but in reality, 
the big players are positioning  

254
00:23:38,080 --> 00:23:44,920
themselves for the move that’s about to come.
During this phase, large players are collecting  

255
00:23:44,920 --> 00:23:51,240
liquidity, by filling their orders without 
causing much movement in price, which could  

256
00:23:51,240 --> 00:23:57,280
otherwise draw attention from other traders.
The price may oscillate slightly, but it  

257
00:23:57,280 --> 00:24:03,360
remains close to the weekly open, keeping 
traders guessing about the next big move.
  

258
00:24:03,360 --> 00:24:09,360
After 1 or 2 days of trading near the open, 
the next phase of manipulation begins. 

259
00:24:09,360 --> 00:24:16,280
The price suddenly moves sharply in one direction. 
This move is quick and decisive, designed to lure  

260
00:24:16,280 --> 00:24:23,080
traders into thinking that a breakout is underway.
For example, if the weekly candle opens and  

261
00:24:23,080 --> 00:24:28,760
trades near the opening level for a few 
days, and suddenly the price shoots down,  

262
00:24:28,760 --> 00:24:33,960
most retail traders will interpret 
this as a strong bearish signal. 

263
00:24:33,960 --> 00:24:39,440
They believe that the market is about to 
go down, and rush to place sell orders.
  

264
00:24:39,440 --> 00:24:45,120
This is exactly what the big players want. 
By creating this sharp move, they trigger  

265
00:24:45,120 --> 00:24:53,200
sell orders from traders and, more importantly, 
stop-loss orders placed by traders who were long. 

266
00:24:53,200 --> 00:24:58,840
This sharp move creates a liquidity pool. The 
traders who enter the market after seeing the  

267
00:24:58,840 --> 00:25:04,680
sharp move, are providing liquidity for 
the big players to execute their trades. 

268
00:25:04,680 --> 00:25:10,760
At this point, the big players have not 
yet fully entered their desired positions. 

269
00:25:10,760 --> 00:25:16,680
They are using this move to mislead the market, 
making other traders believe that the price will  

270
00:25:16,680 --> 00:25:23,320
continue, in the direction of the sharp move. 
 
The sharp move creates a sense of urgency,  

271
00:25:23,320 --> 00:25:28,320
and traders often forget to wait for 
confirmation before entering trades. 

272
00:25:29,080 --> 00:25:35,160
They see the price moving quickly and assume 
that they are missing out on an opportunity.  

273
00:25:35,160 --> 00:25:40,880
This emotional reaction is precisely 
what the big players are counting on. 

274
00:25:40,880 --> 00:25:45,600
Unlike shorter timeframes, where 
manipulation might happen in minutes  

275
00:25:45,600 --> 00:25:52,400
or hours, the weekly chart stretches the 
process over one or even several days. 

276
00:25:52,400 --> 00:25:57,000
This makes it harder for retail 
traders to spot the manipulation,  

277
00:25:57,000 --> 00:26:02,800
because the price action seems more legitimate 
when viewed over a longer timeframe.
  

278
00:26:02,800 --> 00:26:07,560
After trapping retail traders with the 
sharp move, the big players are ready  

279
00:26:07,560 --> 00:26:12,440
for the final phase: distribution.
This is where the real trickery  

280
00:26:12,440 --> 00:26:18,000
happens. The price, now reverses.
The long wick that formed on the weekly  

281
00:26:18,000 --> 00:26:24,400
candle is a classic sign of this reversal.
Traders who entered positions based on the  

282
00:26:24,400 --> 00:26:28,240
sharp move are now trapped, as 
the price moves against them.
  

283
00:26:29,800 --> 00:26:37,400
For example, as the price shot down earlier in the 
week, it now creates a long wick to the downside,  

284
00:26:37,400 --> 00:26:42,280
and reverses, moving upward.
Retail traders who sold into  

285
00:26:42,280 --> 00:26:48,760
the sharp downward move are stuck in losing 
positions, as the market turns against them. 

286
00:26:48,760 --> 00:26:55,400
Their stop-losses get triggered, or they 
panic and close their positions at a loss. 
  

287
00:26:55,400 --> 00:27:01,120
The distribution phase allows the big 
players to exit their positions profitably. 

288
00:27:01,120 --> 00:27:04,880
They had built their positions 
during the accumulation phase and  

289
00:27:04,880 --> 00:27:11,400
used the sharp move to trigger liquidity.
Now, as the price reverses, they begin to  

290
00:27:11,400 --> 00:27:18,180
unwind their positions, selling to traders who are 
desperately trying to exit their losing trades. 
  

291
00:27:18,180 --> 00:27:22,600
Again, if you trade on lower time 
frames, you will get trapped. 

292
00:27:22,600 --> 00:27:27,840
One of the reasons why this type of manipulation 
is so effective on higher timeframes,  

293
00:27:27,840 --> 00:27:33,160
is that it plays out over several days.
Traders are more likely to believe that  

294
00:27:33,160 --> 00:27:39,920
a move is genuine, as it unfolds slowly over 
time, especially when compared to the rapid  

295
00:27:39,920 --> 00:27:46,880
manipulation that occurs on lower timeframes.
 
On a weekly chart, the manipulation doesn’t  

296
00:27:46,880 --> 00:27:54,120
happen in a single candle or a quick spike. 
Instead, it stretches across multiple days,  

297
00:27:54,120 --> 00:27:58,320
making it harder to detect.
Traders might see the price  

298
00:27:58,320 --> 00:28:03,720
moving sharply in one direction and 
assume that the momentum will continue,  

299
00:28:03,720 --> 00:28:11,160
not realizing that they are being led into a trap.
The longer timeframe also gives big players  

300
00:28:11,160 --> 00:28:17,640
more room to build, and distribute their 
positions without drawing too much attention.
  

301
00:28:17,640 --> 00:28:23,920
Additionally, the longer timeframe allows the 
big players to manipulate the market in a way  

302
00:28:23,920 --> 00:28:30,120
that makes the move seem more believable.
A sharp move on a lower timeframe might  

303
00:28:30,120 --> 00:28:36,680
be dismissed as a “fakeout” by experienced 
traders, but on a weekly chart, the same move  

304
00:28:36,680 --> 00:28:42,680
can look like the start of a legitimate trend.
This makes it easier for the big players to  

305
00:28:42,680 --> 00:28:50,040
mislead traders and trap them in losing positions.
